<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The calyces are arranged all around the branches, not very close, slightly raised up to 0.5 mm tall as small mounds composed of eight marginal lobes with small polyp apertures at the summits (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Psammogorgia arbuscula var. dowii Verrill, 1868. YPM 1787 A colony B detail of branches C coenenchymal and anthocodial sclerites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.961.54846.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/442678" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5B</figureCitation>
). Thorny, irregular spindles and some wart-clubs appear often, around the calyx aperture. The anthocodial armature is well developed and composed of spiny spindles arranged in a collaret and points, 0.12-0.20 mm long and 0.032-0.056 mm wide (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Psammogorgia arbuscula var. dowii Verrill, 1868. YPM 1787 A spindles B radiate and cross C wart clubs D anthocodial spindles." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.961.54846.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/442679" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6D</figureCitation>
); its flat rods are with small tubercles and scattered warts. Anthocodial sclerites are red and orange (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Psammogorgia arbuscula var. dowii Verrill, 1868. YPM 1787 A colony B detail of branches C coenenchymal and anthocodial sclerites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.961.54846.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/442678" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
